1903.key_title: Key to the main groups of plants in Victoria

leads.lead_text: Mature plant reproducing by minute spores; spores produced in capsules
Mature plant reproducing by seeds formed following pollination; seeds produced in cones or in fruit derived from a flower ovary

Spore capsules (sporangia) borne on the undersides or margins of fronds or in the axils of modified leaves or scales, sometimes aggregated into cone-like strobili, often with a band of differentiated cells with thickened cell-walls (annulus), rarely fused to form bi- or trilocular synangia, indehiscent or dehiscing with a single slit to one side; spores germinating into short-lived gametophytes that give rise to much larger and independant sporophytes that live on after gametophyte senescence

Spore capsules often borne on an elongate stalk (seta) or sometimes sessile or embedded in the plant, indehiscent or dehiscent by 2â€“7 slits or an operculum; spores germinating into ephemeral to long-lived gametophytes that give rise to dependant, continually attached and often smaller sporophytes comprising the capsule and if present the seta
Capsules elongate, horn shaped and without a seta, frequently produced; photosynthetic organ a pad-like thallus; photosynthetic cells with one or two chloroplasts

Capsules not elongate and horn-shaped, often with an elongate seta; photosynthetic organs leaves clearly differentiated from a stem or if a thallus then photosynthetic cells usually with many more than two chloroplasts

Photosynthetic organ a pad-like thallus or leaves clearly differentiated from a stem; leaves when present arranged in two or three ranks, simple, divided apically into lobes or with adaxial or abaxial lobules, never with a costa but rarely with a unistratose line of elongate cells along centre; leaf cells usually with non-green, usually grey, brownish or hyaline oil body organelles in addition to green chloroplasts when fresh

Photosynthetic organs leaves clearly differentiated from a stem, never a pad-like thallus; leaves arranged in two, three or multiple ranks, often spirally arranged along stem, simple, never divided apically into lobes, rarely with a lobe attached along the midline of the leaf (vaginant lamina), often with a multistratose costa along midline of leaf; leaf cells without visible organelles other than chloroplasts
Plants with flowers; ovules enclosed within carpel(s); leaves simple or compound
Plants usually without flowers; ovules naked on scales typically aggregated into woody or fleshy cones; leaves simple (sometimes very small)
Leaves usually with net-like venation; flower parts usually in whorls of 4 or 5 (rarely 3, 6 or more); taproot present at least at seedling stage; embryo (and usually seedling) with 2 cotyledons
Leaves usually with parallel venation; flower parts usually in whorls of 3 or 6 (rarely 2 or 4); roots fibrous; embryo (and usually seedling) with 1 cotyledon
Plants without flowers; cones woody; trees or shrubs, often producing resin
Male flowers producing anthers; cones fleshy; non-resinous shrubs or subshrubs

1906.key_title: Key to the families of Monocotyledons

breadcrumbs.key_title: Key to the main groups of plants in Victoria

leads.lead_text: Aquatic plants, floating free on or near the water surface, not rooting in substrate
Land or aquatic plants, if aquatic and with floating leaves then rooting in substrate

Plant consisting of small (less than 1 cm long) flat or flattened ovoid leaf or thallus, with or without simple roots from undersurface; plants readily reproducing vegetatively by lateral buds; flowers produced in small pits on upper surface, microscopic and rarely observed
Plants conspicuous, with leaves c. 5 cm long or more, the petioles much inflated and spongy, roots abundant, feathery; flowers conspicuous (c. 5 cm diam.), mauve, produced in spikes
Marine aquatics, or aquatics of non-marine habitats with leaves permanently submerged, but inflorescence sometimes emergent from water
Terrestrial or semi-aquatic plants, or aquatics with leaves floating or emergent from water
Plants of marine or brackish habitats
Plants of fresh water
Leaves ligulate
Leaves without ligules
Plants of brackish habitats (including estuaries, rarely extending to the intertidal zone); leaves 1 mm wide or less; flowers unisexual, solitary or clustered in axils
Marine plants of deep waters and rock-pools; leaves at least 4 mm wide
[link through]
Leaf blade and sheath shed leaving a circular scar; flowers unisexual, enclosed within leaf-sheaths
Leaf blade shed but sheath persistent and fibrous; flowers bisexual, in several terminal spikes
[link through]
[link through]
Leaves elliptic to ovate, c. 1 cm wide or more; flowers with perianth (males with 3 segments, females with 6)
Leaves narrow linear, to 1 mm wide; flowers without perianth
Flowers bisexual, borne at the end of a long, spirally coiled peduncle
Flowers unisexual, in short spikes, remaining enclosed in sheathing leaf-bases
Flowers bisexual, in emergent spikes; perianth segments 4
Flowers unisexual, remaining submerged; perianth segments 0, 3 or 6
[link through]
Leaves ovate to linear, mostly much more than 1 mm wide, but if ever less, then with finely toothed margins
Leaves narrow-linear, less than 1 mm wide, with entire margins
[link through]

Flowers lacking perianth, packed in thickish spike, subtended and partially enclosed by a tubular bract (spathe), margins overlapping or connate at base; apical part of spike male only or with a sterile appendix, lower part of spike female or bisexual; fleshy usually rhizomatous herb, usually near swamps or watercourses
Flowers with a perianth or if perianth lacking, flowers not arranged in spatheate spikes
Flowers unisexual
Flowers bisexual

Flowers inconspicuous, often minute, subtended (and often enclosed by) paired or solitary, overlapping bracts or scales, in heads or spikelets; perianth absent or of 1â€“8 scales or bristles, usually concealed within bracts
Flowers conspicuous (but not always coloured), or if inconspicuous at least with distinct perianth parts
Male and female flowers small, mixed in spherical heads 2â€“8 mm diam., lacking conspicuous bracts; mostly marsh or aquatic plants
Flowers in spikelets surrounded by glume-like bracts
[link through]
Wiry plants with jointed stems; leaves reduced to sheathing bracts (bracts overlapping at base); male and female plants separate (except sometimes in Lepyrodia)
Leaves well developped, or if ever reduced to sheathing bracts then these fused at the base and plants with both male and female flowers or flowers bisexual
Tiny, tufted annuals; male and female flowers mixed in terminal heads subtended and exceeded by 2â€“6 equal or subequal bracts
Habit various; if inflorescence ever a terminal head then flowers bisexual
Inflorescence green or greenish, with a pair of prominent, erect sheathing bracts enclosing the flowers and their small, membranous, subtending bracts
Inflorescence red, flower cluster subtended by 4â€“6 more or less equal sheathing bracts, individual flowers (ovaries and stamens) not subtended by bracts
[link through]

Flowers arranged in cylindric or distichous spikelets or spikes (rarely 1-flowered), rarely subtended by a pair of sterile bracts; individual flowers subtended by a solitary bract (glume); leaf-sheath usually with fused margins; stems cylindric, flattened or 3-sided, with solid internodes (sedges)

Flowers arranged in distichous (sometimes 1-flowered) spikelets, usually subtended by a pair of sterile bracts (glumes); individual flowers enclosed by a pair of bracts (lemma and palea), or if ever only one bract present, then fertile flowers only 1 per spikelet; leaf-sheath usually with free margins; stems usually cylindric, with hollow internodes (grasses)
Plants monoecious, male flowers borne above females in inflorescence; aquatic or semi-aquatic plants
Plants dioecious; mostly terrestrial
Perianth segments not petaloid; flowers sessile, in spikes or globular clusters; leaves linear, flattened or triangular in cross-section
Perianth segments in 2 distinct whorls, the outermost petaloid; flowers pedicellate, whorled; at least the emergent leaves with a distinct ovate to sagittate blade
Climbers, usually with retrorse spines along stems; leaves ovate, with prominent reticulate venation; eastern Victoria only
Non-climbers, or, if plants every climbing then venation linear, lacking prominent reticulate venation
Leaves well-developed; perianth segments more or less membranous or somewhat fleshy; fruit containing 1â€“few seeds
Leaves reduced to sheathing bracts; perianth segments scarious; fruit containing many small seeds
Carpels not fused or shortly united at base only
Carpels united for the greater part or carpel solitary
Tufted annuals or perennials, less than 10 cm high; land plants (but often growing near water)
Perennials, more than 10 cm high; aquatic or marsh plants
Inflorescence green or greenish, with a pair of prominent, erect sheathing bracts enclosing the flowers and their small, membranous, subtending bracts
Inflorescence red, flower cluster subtended by 4â€“6 more or less equal sheathing bracts, individual flowers (ovaries and stamens) not subtended by bracts
[link through]
Flowers borne in once-forked spikes; perianth of a single white segment; anthers 6â€“12, purple; carpels 3â€“6
Flowers borne in simple spikes or panicles; perianth of 3 or more segments (but inconspicuous in Juncaginaceae)
[link through]
Perianth segments, stamens and carpels each 4
Perianth segments, stamens and carpels not each 4
[link through]
Perianth segments in 2 distinct whorls, the outermost petaloid; at least the emergent leaves with a distinct ovate to sagittate blade
Perianth segments all similar, not petaloid; leaves linear, terete or strap-shaped
Ovary superior or perianth of petals and/or sepals absent
Ovary inferior, perianth well-developed

Flowers inconspicuous, often minute, within imbricate bracts or scales (glumes), in spikelets; perianth absent or of 18 scales or bristles, usually concealed within bracts (chiefly grasses and sedges)
Flowers conspicuous (but not always coloured), or if inconspicuous at least with distinct perianth parts rather than scales or bristles

Tiny, tufted plants; male and female flowers mixed in terminal heads subtended and exceeded by 2â€“6 equal or subequal bracts; individual flowers sometimes separated by a minute membranous bract; fruit a dehiscent, 1-seeded capsule
Plants various, if ever male and female flowers mixed in heads then bracts (glumes) separating individual flowers conspicuous; fruit indehiscent, 1-seeded
Inflorescence green or greenish, with a pair of prominent, erect sheathing bracts enclosing the flowers; individual flowers separated by a minute membranous bract
Inflorescence reddish, with 2 or 3 pairs of equal sheathing bracts enclosing the flowers; individual flowers not subtended by bracts
[link through]

Flowers arranged in cylindric or distichous spikelets or spikes (rarely 1-flowered), rarely subtended by a pair of sterile bracts; individual flowers subtended by a solitary bract (glume); leaf-sheath usually with fused margins; stems cylindric, flattened or 3-sided (sedges)

Flowers arranged in distichous (sometimes 1-flowered) spikelets, usually subtended by a pair of sterile bracts (glumes); individual flowers enclosed by a pair of bracts (lemma and palea), or if ever only one bract present, then fertile flowers only 1 per spikelet; leaf-sheath usually with free margins; stems usually cylindric, with hollow internodes (grasses)
Perianth segments 4 (inner pair small); stamen 1; uncommon yellow-flowered, tufted semi-aquatic
Perianth segments 6
[link through]
Leaves compound; stems massive, woody, erect and undivided (palms)
Leaves simple or absent
Perianth sepaloid (green, brown or translucent)
Perianth petaloid (white or coloured), but sometimes segments small
Carpels fused; style solitary, with 3 stigmas
Carpels free or nearly so; stigmas sessile
Stamens 3
Stamens 6 (sometimes 3 much longer than others)

Rhizome bright red; leaves tufted, linear, to 1.2 m long, plicate; scape up to 2.5 m tall; inflorescence a dense cylindircal panicle, with numerous yellow flowers; style and lowermost anther turned sideways
Rhizome absent or not conspicuously bright red, but if ever somewhat reddish, neither with leaves long and plicate nor with scape approaching 2 m high
[link through]
Inner perianth segments united; flowers short-lived with yellowish, tissue-like petals; inflorescence a dense spherical head on an undivided, wiry scape
Inner perianth segments free; other features in combination not as above
[link through]

Tufted plants, stems commonly annual, or if prostrate, scrambling or twining, then either leafless or leaves sessile; rhizomatous or with a bulbous or cormous rootstock; inflorescence a raceme or panicle, not subtended by spathe-like bracts

Prostrate, scrambling, much-branched plant with perennial, succulent stems; leaves ovate with sheathing petioles; rooting readily from nodes; inflorescence of 1ew flowers subtended by a single or pair of spathe-like bracts
Aquatic plants; flowers mauve and yellow in a terminal spike-like raceme; leaf-blade ovate, on long petiole
Land plants, rarely growing in marshy situations and then with features not as above

Tufted plants, stems commonly annual, or if prostrate, scrambling or twining, then either leafless or leaves sessile; rhizomatous or with a bulbous or cormous rootstock; inflorescence a raceme or panicle, not subtended by spathe-like bracts

Prostrate, scrambling, much-branched plant with perennial, succulent stems; leaves ovate with sheathing petioles; rooting readily from nodes; inflorescence of 1-few flowers subtended by a single or pair of spathe-like bracts
Flower lacking labellum; stamens 3 or 6, not assoicated with the style
Flower usually with distinct labellum; stamens 1, united with style or style held between anther locules
Aquatic plants with leaf-blades ovate, floating on water surface; flowers emergent or floating, showy, whitish with red-purple blotch at base; submerged cleistogamous flowers also produced
Terrestrial plants, or if semi-aquatic, then leaf blades more or less linear and emergent from water
Stamens 3
Stamens 6
Mostly leafy herbs, always with chlorophyll (i.e. some parts green), growing and flowering above ground level
Leafless herbs without chlorophyll (i.e. with no green parts), growing and flowering within leaf-litter layer of wet, shaded forests
Flowers zygomorphic, perianth tubular, externally tomentose; inflorescence a one-sided raceme
Flowers actinomorphic, or if zygomorphic then features not as above
[link through]
[link through]
Labellum derived from modified perianth segment; stamen and style united, with stamen distal to style
Labellum derived from staminodes; style held between anther locules, the style extending beyond the anther
[link through]

1907.key_title: Key to the families of Dicotyledons

breadcrumbs.key_title: Key to the main groups of plants in Victoria

leads.lead_text: Aquatics with all leaves permanently submerged and divided into numerous filiform or linear segments, often rapidly shrivelling upon exposure to air (but inflorescences sometimes emergent)
Land plants or semi-aquatics, with at least the terminal leaves (when present) normally exposed to the air (but leaves sometimes lying flat on water surface)
Leaves whorled; flowers minute, inconspicuous
Leaves alternate or opposite; flowers conspicuous
Leaves pinnately dissected; flowers in a terminal spike; perianth present
Leaves dichotomously forked 1â€“3 times; perianth absent
Leaves opposite; flowers with dark red or blackish perianth segments
Leaves alternate; flowers with yellowish segments
Plant free-floating; leaves interspersed with bladders; flower zygomorphic, conspicuously spurred, emergent on erect peduncle; fruit a capsule, ripening in the air
Plant rooted in mud; bladders absent; flower actinomorphic, barely emergent; pedicel recurving in fruit (head of achenes ripening under water)
Herbs lacking chlorophyll (stems brownish or yellowish); leaves reduced to scales, or absent; fruit a capsule
Green plants; if ever leaves absent at maturity, then plants woody; fruit various
Slender, twining, stem-parasites; flowers actinomorphic, minute, usually in globoid clusters
Stout, erect, root parasites; flowers zygomorphic, conspicuous, more or less tubular, arranged in spikes
Leafless, twining, stem-parasites, rooted only in juvenile phase; flowers 3-partite; fruit a drupe with viscid flesh
Plants rooted at maturity, or if stem-parasites then not twining, leaves normally present and flowers 4â€“5-partite
Shrubs and trees with jointed, grooved, filiform branchlets; leaves present as whorls of 5 or more minute teeth, encircling branchlet joints; infructescence a woody cone
Plants not combining the above features
Perianth of 2 (rarely more) distinct whorls (sepals and petals), differing from each other in shape, size or colour (calyx or corolla sometimes deciduous at anthesis)
Perianth absent or of 1 whorl, or of 2 or more similar whorls (sometimes falling off as an operculum at anthesis)
Petals free to base (rarely shortly united near the tips)
Petals all united (or rarely with 1 free petal), at least at the base, the tubular part sometimes short
Ovary inferior or semi-inferior
Ovary superior (but sometimes closely surrounded by a narrow calyx-tube)
Apparent petals (petaloid staminodes) numerous, brightly coloured or white; succulents
Petals 2â€“9
Stamens numerous (more than 10)
Stamens 10 or fewer
Leaves lacking stipules, entire, aromatic with translucent oil dots
Leaves with stipules, or if stipules lacking, then leaves entire, usually non-aromatic but never with oil dots
Leaves opposite, trifoliolate (sometimes apparently whorled)
Leaves alternate
Leaves without stipules; rare evergreen rainforest trees of far east
Leaves with stipules; herbs or shrubs, if ever small trees, then garden-escapes and often deciduous

Aquatic herbs (sometimes growing on mud), usually with most leaves submerged and pinnately divided into filiform segments; flowers in terminal spikes projecting above the water's surface, often unisexual
Terrestrial plants, or if aquatic, submerged leaves not pinnate, and flowers bisexual
Trees or shrubs (sometimes climbing)
Herbs (sometimes semi-woody in garden-escaped Fuchsia)

Flowers sessile or subsessile, clustered into a head, surrounded by an involucre of 4 spreading creamy-white bracts, each 2.5â€“3.5 cm long; fruit a pinkish globular fleshy head c. 1â€“3 cm diam.; garden-escaped shrub or small tree
Plants not combining the above features
Flowers in umbels (simple or compound), usually small and greenish; ovary 2-carpellate
Flowers not in umbels (but sometimes clustered in cymes); ovary various
Fruit dry; leaves commonly ternately or pinnately divided, rarely 2 cm long
Fruit succulent, berry-like, leaves variously pinnate, palmately divided or entire, or if fruit dry, then leaves entire, linear, and usually more than 2 cm long
Branch-parasites; leaves entire; fruit a succulent drupe with sticky flesh
Non-parasitic plants, rooted in soil or mud
Spiny shrubs
Shrubs or herbs without spines; fruit non-succulent
Leaves alternate, palmately lobed; fruit a succulent, many-seeded berry c. 2 cm long
Leaves and spines opposite (leaves usually present only on younger stems); fruit a 3-partite capsule
Leaves simple and entire (if ever toothed, then bearing stellate hairs); sepals 5
Leaves either compound, or simple and toothed, never stellate-hairy; sepals 4 or 6â€“8
Leaves glabrous, aromatic, with translucent oil dots; style simple
Leaves hairy (often with stellate hairs), neither aromatic nor oil-dotted; style 3-branched
Leaves trifoliolate; sepals 6â€“8; fruit a 2-locular capsule
Leaves simple; sepals 4; fruit a 1-seeded nut or nutlet
Shrubs or climbers growing at margins of rainforest; leaves opposite, ovate, 1.5â€“4 cm wide; petals minute or apparently absent, distinctly smaller than sepals
Plants not containing the features above
Perianth whorls green and sepaloid (petals absent, epicalyx sometimes developed); fruit an achene, commonly with barbed spines or prickles at the apex; flowers in spikes, heads, clusters or corymbs
Inner perianth whorl petaloid, sometimes small, epicalyx absent; fruit not spinose or prickly
Flowers in umbels or sessile in heads; petals 5; styles normally 2; plants often aromatic (includes Hydrocotyle and Trachymene which are now included in Araliaceae, see note under family description)
Flowers not in umbels or heads; petals 4 or 5; styles 1â€“4; plants not aromatic
Style single, stigma lobed; ovary elongate; seeds numerous; petals conspicuous
Styles 2â€“4, stigmas usually plumose; ovary short and broad; seeds 1â€“4; petals often minute
Carpels and styles free, or the carpels shortly united near the base
Carpels and/or styles distinctly united for the greater part, or ovary consisting of a single carpel
Sepals and petals each 2 or 3
Sepals and petals more than 3
Small herbs; leaves opposite, succulent
Shrubs or vines; leaves alternate, not succulent
Montane to alpine shrubs with aromatic (peppery to the taste), oblong to oblanceolate leaves
Vine or liane of lowland forests and rainforests; leaves broadly ovate, cordate at base
Stamens more than twice as many as petals
Stamens not more than twice as many as petals
Herbs, lacking stipules; perianth segments inserted below carpels
Herbs with stipules, or shrubs; flowers various
Montane to alpine shrubs with aromatic leaves (peppery to the taste); sepals 2â€“4
Leaves not aromatic; herbs or shrubs; sepals 5
Perianth segments inserted below ovary (hypogynous); shrubs or twiners with showy, yellow, usually emarginate petals
Perianth segments inserted on short tube or rim extending above the ovary base (perigynous); herbs with stipules, or shrubs with entire, non-yellow petals
Small annual herbs or succulent perennials
Perennial shrubs or trees
Receptacle elongate, with numerous (usually more than 100) carpels; non-succulent herbs
Receptacle short, carpels 4 or 5; more or less succulent herbs
Leaves simple, sometimes shallowly toothed, under 10 cm long; shrubs or twiners with rather showy, yellow, bisexual flowers
Leaves pinnate, longer than 20 cm; trees with small, unisexual flowers
Flowers distinctly zygomorphic
Flowers actinomorphic or very nearly so
Stamens more than twice as many as petals, always more than 6, or both stamens and petals numerous
Stamens no more than twice as many as petals, or petals 2 and stamens 6
Stamens all united into a single tube or column, free part of filaments short to long
Stamens all free, or clustered into bundles
Leaves linear, with revolute margins; flowers unisexual, petals white, much exceeding sepals; ovary 3-locular
Leaves otherwise; flowers bisexual or if ever unisexual, then petals hardly exceeding sepals
Leaves bipinnate; flowers in short spikes; ovary 1-locular
Leaves not bipinnate; flowers solitary or in cymes; ovary 2-many-locular
[link through]
Plants aquatic, with long-petiolate leaves floating on or shortly emergent from water surface, suborbicular, more or less peltate; petals in several whorls
Plants terrestrial; leaves basally attached; petals in 1 (rarely 2) whorls
Perianth segments inserted on short tube or rim extending above the ovary base (perigynous); carpel and ovule each 1; fruit a drupe; plants sometimes deciduous (Prunus)
Perianth segments inserted below ovary (hypogynous); plants evergreen (except Actinidia)
Flowers sessile in globose heads or cylindric spikes; individual flowers small, petals minute, far exceeded by the conspicuous cream to yellow stamens; fruit a dry, several-seeded pod (Acacia)
Flowers not in heads or spikes; petals more or less conspicuous; fruit not a pod
[link through]
Herbs (usually annual) with watery sap or yellowish latex; sepals 2, distinct, or united into a conical calyptra, soon deciduous; styles 1 or absent
Perennial herbs, shrubs or trees; sepals 3â€“8; styles 1-several
Leaves succulent, often fascicled; fruit a reddish drupe; stiff, often spinescent shrub of saline ground in north and north-west
Leaves not succulent and fascicled; fruit and habit not as above
Leaves alternate, petiolate, trifoliate; fruit a capsule, valvate or dehiscent in distal half
Plants not combining features as above
Herbs; leaves succulent, alternate, irregularly multifid
Plants not combining features as above
Woody vine; stems with segmented pith; lower surface of leaves with stellate hairs; fruit a densely tomentose berry with green pulp (Kiwifruit)
Plants not combining features as above
Leaves alternate; fruit a drupe; tall shrubs or small to medium trees of eastern Victoria
Leaves opposite (sometimes apparently whorled); fruit a capsule or berry; herbs or shrubs to c. 2 m high, rarely trees to 12 m high
Plants with at least some stellate hairs; flowers large and showy, white or pink with numerous yellow anthers borne on a hypogynous disc; style 1
Plants glabrous or with simple hairs; flowers not as above; styles 2 or more
Flowers yellow; leaves simple
Flowers white, pink or magenta; leaves trifoliolate or pinnate
Climbing or trailing plants with tendrils; eastern Victoria, or naturalized more widely; fruit a berry (but the wall sometimes hard or leathery)
Herbs, shrubs or trees, if ever climbing then lacking tendrils; fruit various
Leaves palmate, with 5 distinct leaflets; flowers small, dull; seeds 1â€“4
Leaves simple, shallowly to deeply lobed but not palmate; flowers relatively large, colourful; seeds numerous
Herbs
Shrubs or trees
Perianth segments in several whorls of 3; yellow-flowered garden-escape, with spinose, toothed leaves and stipules
Perianth in 2 whorls of 4â€“6
Leaves usually spine-toothed (occasionally entire, but then with apical mucro), dark green and glossy above; perianth segments in 2 whorls of 4; fruit a bright red drupe (Holly)
Leaves not spinose (but branches or stipules sometimes spine-tipped); flowers and fruit various
Leaves pinnate
Leaves entire (rarely plants apparently leafless)
Leaflets 2, succulent; soft-wooded subshrubs
Leaflets 2â€“many, not succulent; true woody shrubs or trees
Branches with paired spines or stipules; inflorescence a cylindric to ovoid spike; perianth parts small, much exceeded by the stamens; weed of northern Victoria
Branches unarmed or with single spines; inflorescence not a spike; perianth parts usually apparent, not or not much exceeded by the stamens

Leaves strongly aromatic (usually spicy or fruity), either with translucent oil dots in the leaves, or with milky resinous sap
Leaves not aromatic (sometimes with an unpleasant odour); plants lacking obvious oil dots and milky sap
Leaves opposite, with translucent oil dots, usually more or less fruitily aromatic; sap not milky; fruit dehiscent
Leaves alternate, lacking translucent oil dots, peppery-aromatic; sap milky, resinous; fruit a pink drupe with crustaceous skin
Shrubs; flowers relatively large, yellow; fruit a linear to oblong pod
Trees; flowers small, not brightly coloured; fruit not a pod
[link through]
Fruit a 3-lobed capsule, seed with large fleshy aril; rare evergreen tree of extreme east
Fruit a cluster of 2â€“5 flattened, winged, 1-seeded samaras; fast-growing deciduous trees, escaped from cultivation
Stamens united in an urn-shaped tube around the pistil; flowers fragrant, pendent; fruit a purple to black, often mottled berry; branches usually spinose
Stamens free, or united at the very base; fruit a berry, capsule, schizocarp or drupe
Low shrubs or subshrubs of saline ground; leaves small (under 1 cm long), opposite, connate at base; usually greyish from secreted salt; ovary 1-locular, enclosed in fruit by persistent calyx
Habit and foliage not as above
Small non-glandular shrubs; sepals 4; petals inconspicuous, 0 or 4; fruit strongly flattened, less than 1 cm long, 2-locular, dehiscent, with 1 seed per locule
Plants not combining the above characteristics
Stamens alternating with and equal in number to petals
Stamens opposite petals or twice as many as petals
Fruit a drupe; leaves opposite, virtually odourless, lacking oil dots
Fruit a berry or capsule, or if ever a drupe (rarely) then leaves aromatic, with translucent oil dots
Flowers with a conspicuous disc; petals less than 3 (rarely to 4) mm long; style often lobed at apex; seeds sometimes arillate
Flowers without a disc; petals longer than 3 mm; style undivided; seeds without an aril
Leaves reduced and scale-like (to c. 4 mm long); flowers in terminal narrow cylindric spikes; capsule small, ovoid, seeds not arillate; garden-escaped shrubs or trees

Leaves crenate or lobed, broad, sometimes aromatic; fruit splitting into 5 long- beaked (or awned) 1-seeded fruitlets
Leaves almost or quite entire, or if ever toothed, then fruits not splitting into beaked or awned segments

Stamens all perfect
Some (rarely all) stamens modified into staminodia
Plants with (usually stellate) hairs
Plants more or less glabrous
Leaves aromatic; ovary 5-locular; fruit dry, a capsule or schizocarp; garden escape
Leaves not aromatic; ovary 1â€“3-locular; fruit a green drupe; rare, yellow-green shrubs of far eastern lowlands
Shrubs aromatic; leaves with translucent oil dots; fruit capsular with 1â€“5 follicles
